INSERT INTO `nge_posts` VALUES('469', '1', '2019-05-26 13:27:41', '2019-05-26 06:27:41', '<p>[vc_row][vc_column][vc_column_text]</p>\r\n<p>When registering your business you need to know what status you want to register as.<br /><strong>Sole Proprietorship:</strong><br />Registering as a sole proprietorship means that one person owns and operates the business. This person owns the whole capital and receives all the profits of the company. It also means that all obligations and liabilities are the responsibility of the proprietor. A business registered as a sole proprietorship, according to the Real Tax Regime, is considered as a small taxpayer. The problem with the sole proprietorship is the liability. If your business is small and risk of having large debts/liabilities is small, then registering as a sole proprietorship may be the best choice to pay less taxes.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Partnership:<br /></strong>Two or more persons together can register as a partnership. This is legally similar to a sole proprietorship, however there are two or more people registered as business owners. It is advised to create a written partnership contract to minimise the risk of any issues that may arise. All the partners are responsible for any debts and obligations.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Limited Partnership:</strong><br />A limited partnership is similar to a general partnership, however one of the partners has “limited liability.” This means that the partner that has limited liability is not personally liable for any debts and obligations. This may be the case when a partner wants to invest money into the business, but does not want to be personally liable for the business.. If a limited partnership is not notified to the Ministry of Commerce, it will be considered as a general partnership.<strong><br /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Private Limited Company:<br />This legal company status corresponds to the “traditional enterprise” and is composed of shareholders and directors. Shareholders and directors are not personally liable for the company’s debts. A private limited company is composed of 2 to 30 shareholders.</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>For more information and tips on how to choose a status, please see <a href=\"http://ngeayngeay.co/choosing-your-business-status/\">“Choosing your business status”</a> under our Business Tips section. </strong></p>\r\n<p>[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row]</p>', 'Should I register as a sole proprietor, partnership or limited liability company?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'should-i-register-as-a-sole-proprietor-partnership-or-limited-liability-company-2', '', '', '2019-05-26 13:28:34', '2019-05-26 06:28:34', '', '0', 'http://localhost:8888/ngeayngeay/?post_type=faq&#038;p=469', '0', 'faq', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `nge_posts` VALUES('470', '1', '2019-05-26 13:29:55', '2019-05-26 06:29:55', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Whether you are registered as a sole proprietorship, partnership or limited liability company, every business needs to register with</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:list -->\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Ministry of Commerce</li>\r\n<li>General Department of Tax</li>\r\n<li>Ministry of Labour and Vocational Training</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<!-- /wp:list -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Then depending on your business activities, you will need to obtain licenses from various ministries, see <a href=\"http://ngeayngeay.co/license/ministries-and-licenses-in-cambodia/\">here for information on licenses</a></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Which Ministries do I need to register with?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'which-ministries-do-i-need-to-register-with', '', '', '2019-05-26 13:30:10', '2019-05-26 06:30:10', '', '0', 'http://localhost:8888/ngeayngeay/?post_type=faq&#038;p=470', '0', 'faq', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `nge_posts` VALUES('471', '1', '2019-05-26 13:30:59', '2019-05-26 06:30:59', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>For registration of limited liability company with the Ministry of Commerce you will need the documents below:</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:list -->\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Company name in both khmer and english</li>\r\n<li>Company single share value</li>\r\n<li>Scanned copy of proof of location (utility bill, rental agreement, land title)</li>\r\n<li>An e-mail address</li>\r\n<li>Scanned copies of Khmer ID or Passport for all shareholders/directors</li>\r\n<li>List of all your employees. You will need to state the gender and if they are khmer or foreigners.</li>\r\n<li>A digital copy (scanned copy) of your memorandum and articles of association.</li>\r\n<li>A bank account. For the payment online, you need a bank account at ACLEDA bank. If you don’t, you can still perform your payment offline, through another bank, by going to the ministry of commerce.</li>\r\n<li>Proof of Investment capital. The amount will depend on your business activities, it is formally $1000, however we have found that practically this can be up to $5000. You should open a business account in any bank you want to and put the required amount on it. The bank will issue a proof that you actually made a deposit and then you have to provide it to the MoC. The MoC needs to know that you have enough capital to operate the business initially.</li>\r\n<li>Passport Photograph</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<!-- /wp:list -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>For more information on the what documents are needed for sole proprietorship and partnerships go to our registration page.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'What documents do I need?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'what-documents-do-i-need-2', '', '', '2019-05-26 13:31:11', '2019-05-26 06:31:11', '', '0', 'http://localhost:8888/ngeayngeay/?post_type=faq&#038;p=471', '0', 'faq', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `nge_posts` VALUES('472', '1', '2019-05-26 13:31:45', '2019-05-26 06:31:45', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>If you decide not register the primary risk is that your business may be shut down or you will be subject to fees and penalties, these may vary depending upon your business activities and size. Additionally you will also be limiting the opportunities for your business to grow by increasing your personal risk (due to personal liability), having an unprotected brand name, being unable to export and increasing the difficulty of accessing financing.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Click <a href=\"http://ngeayngeay.co/overview/\">here</a> for more information on why you should register.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'What are the risks if I don\'t register?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'what-are-the-risks-if-i-dont-register', '', '', '2019-05-26 13:31:56', '2019-05-26 06:31:56', '', '0', 'http://localhost:8888/ngeayngeay/?post_type=faq&#038;p=472', '0', 'faq', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `nge_posts` VALUES('473', '1', '2019-05-26 13:32:26', '2019-05-26 06:32:26', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>The taxes that you have to pay are:</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:list -->\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>VAT – 10%</li>\r\n<li>Tax on Profit – 20% of profit or 1% of revenue (whichever is greater)</li>\r\n<li>Withholding tax – 10% rental, 15% salaries</li>\r\n<li>Salary Tax – 5%- 20%</li>\r\n<li>Annual Tax Patent – $100 (small taxpayers), $300 (medium tax payers), $750-$1250 (large taxpayers)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<!-- /wp:list -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>For more information click <a href=\"http://ngeayngeay.co/after-registration/\">here</a></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'How much tax do I have to pay?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'how-much-tax-do-i-have-to-pay', '', '', '2019-05-26 13:32:34', '2019-05-26 06:32:34', '', '0', 'http://localhost:8888/ngeayngeay/?post_type=faq&#038;p=473', '0', 'faq', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `nge_posts` VALUES('474', '1', '2019-05-26 13:33:29', '2019-05-26 06:33:29', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Unfortunately sometimes businesses fail, when this happens, you will need to go through the following steps to properly close your business. The steps that you need to take depends on the status of your company.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Limited Company/Representative/Branch:<br /></strong>In case it occurs, we want to give you all the keys to administratively close your business. When you are in a really difficult situation, and if there is no other possibility, such as a merger, and closing your business seems to be the best choice, the following are the steps you should take. Liquidation is synonym of Bankruptcy, which means your situation is bad enough to close your business and you cannot afford to pay your debts.<br />A lot of entrepreneurs who fail in business tend to just walk away, without taking time to properly close their business. If you don’t address the situation, the Ministry of Commerce will still consider you as a taxpayer and the MoC will be waiting for you to file the annual declaration. When they realize that you don’t pay your taxes anymore, they will also realize your business has closed. There should be nothing left from your business, no assets, but the risk is that directors and shareholders can still be sued. What are the penalties if you fail to liquidate/dissolve your business? Cost?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Liquidation and dissolution are two distinct steps.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:list -->\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>A dissolution is the step that comes first. It refers to the decision of closing a business. There cannot be a liquidation without a dissolution previously. This decision permits to keep the business “alive” before the total liquidation of the company, and to name the person who will actually liquidate the company.</li>\r\n<li>When you liquidate, you agree to sell all your business assets. This stage of the business closure follows the dissolution, and consist of transforming all the business assets into money, for instance machines and equipment. You assign a value to every asset you own as a business.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<!-- /wp:list -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>So what are the steps to close your business properly?</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Step 1: Discuss the liquidation/dissolution<br /></strong>First, you have to gather both directors and shareholders to discuss the liquidation/dissolution. A two third of the majority is required to close your business. It is called the resolution.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Step 2: Notify the Ministry of Commerce<br /></strong>You can do it directly from the online system of the Ministry of Commerce. Select your company, then “maintain company” and finally file “Notice of Intention to Liquidate/Dissolve”. Afterwards, you should upload:</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:list -->\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>a statement of intent to liquidate or a statement of intent to dissolve. These documents must be completed with your shareholders.</li>\r\n<li>The resolution</li>\r\n<li>The resolution date</li>\r\n<li>Your own consent on the liquidation/dissolution.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<!-- /wp:list -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Step 3: Prepare the closure<br /></strong>From this stage, the company is required to stop operating, except for all the tasks required to close the business. The official Notice of Intention to dissolve issued by the Ministry of Commerce should be sent to every creditor of the company, to let them know about the closure. To make it official, the closure of your business should be published in the newspapers. It is part of your duties to inform them about the closure. You can then start to liquidate the business, by distributing assets to shareholders.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Step 4: Dissolution of the company<br /></strong>Then, the Ministry of Commerce will issue a Certificate of Dissolution. This is the official document that confirms your business doesn’t exist anymore. At this time, you will be required to fill Articles of Dissolution. This process costs 480 000 Riels.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>On the online system, click on your company and then click on “File articles of dissolution”. You will have to upload:</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:list -->\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Articles of dissolution</li>\r\n<li>Proof of publication issued by the newspapers you chose</li>\r\n<li>Liquidation report</li>\r\n<li>Tax statement. What is it?</li>\r\n<li>Resolution</li>\r\n<li>Meeting minutes</li>\r\n<li>Resolution date</li>\r\n<li>Your own consent</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<!-- /wp:list -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>After you gathered and uploaded all these documents, the status of your company on the online system will be changed to “dissolved.”</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>The Department of Taxation should also do an official audit of the company, but this process is really expensive.  Closing a business has a cost. The company may still have money left to cover these last expenses, but it’s not often the case. However, just walking away from your business could cause you more problems than closing your business properly. What problems? </p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p><strong>Costs:</strong></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:list -->\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>File Notice of Intention to Liquidate: free</li>\r\n<li>File Articles of Dissolution: 480000 Riels </li>\r\n<li>File Court Order Dissolution: 480000 Riels </li>\r\n<li>File Application for Strike Off: free </li>\r\n<li>File Court Order for Strike Off: free </li>\r\n<li>Lodge Court Order to Dissolve: free</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<!-- /wp:list -->', 'How do I close/stop my business?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'how-do-i-close-stop-my-business-2', '', '', '2019-05-26 13:33:41', '2019-05-26 06:33:41', '', '0', 'http://localhost:8888/ngeayngeay/?post_type=faq&#038;p=474', '0', 'faq', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `nge_posts` VALUES('475', '1', '2019-05-26 13:34:17', '2019-05-26 06:34:17', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>It may occur that during the registration process you are asked for a bribe or a “small fee,” although this is decreasing, particularly through online payments it still does occur when making in person payments. Often these bribes will be asked to speed up processes or not delay processes, we strongly recommend not paying any bribes as it puts you and your business at risk.</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>Dealing with bribes can be difficult, below we have outlined some steps if you get asked a for a bribe:</p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:list -->\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Remain calm and use your negotiation skills</li>\r\n<li>Take notes of the conversation, noting down who and what was said</li>\r\n<li>Clarify what is being asked of you</li>\r\n<li>Question whether the request is legitimate and ask the official where the “fee” is displayed or stated</li>\r\n<li>Refuse is the official cannot supply official validity of the fee</li>\r\n<li>If the official still demands, ask to see the official’s supervisor</li>\r\n<li>If that is refused or the supervisor also asks for payment, offer to pay the fee for subject to being given an official receipt.</li>\r\n<li>Report the incident with the Head Office of the Department or Ministry</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<!-- /wp:list -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>For further reading see Transparency International’s document – <a href=\"http://ngeayngeay.co/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/Countering_Small_Bribes.pdf\">Countering Small Bribes</a></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\r\n\r\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\r\n<p>If you require further information please contact <a href=\"http://www.ticambodia.org/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">Transparency International</a></p>\r\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'What do I do if I get asked for a bribe?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'what-do-i-do-if-i-get-asked-for-a-bribe', '', '', '2019-05-26 13:34:28', '2019-05-26 06:34:28', '', '0', 'http://localhost:8888/ngeayngeay/?post_type=faq&#038;p=475', '0', 'faq', '', '0');
