INSERT INTO `nge_posts` VALUES('1185', '1', '2019-06-20 22:03:41', '2019-06-20 15:03:41', '<h2>NSSF Registration</h2>		\n		<p>After registration with the Ministry of Labour, you will need to register with the NSSF</p>		\n		<p>For the NSSF registration you will need</p><ul><li>Tax patent</li><li>Certificate of Incorporation</li><li>Employee list</li><li>ID/Passport for the Chairperson/owner/representative of the business</li><li>NSSF Forms</li></ul><p>Go the General Labour or អគ្គការងារ building, level 3 and hand in the documents.</p>		\n			<iframe frameborder=\"0\" scrolling=\"no\" marginheight=\"0\" marginwidth=\"0\" src=\"https://maps.google.com/maps?q=ministry%20of%20labour&amp;t=m&amp;z=14&amp;output=embed&amp;iwloc=near\" aria-label=\"ministry of labour\"></iframe>', 'NSSF Registration', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '1183-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-06-20 22:03:41', '2019-06-20 15:03:41', '', '1183', 'http://maskred.com/BIGkeenProject/BK_ngeayngeay/2019/06/20/1183-revision-v1/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `nge_posts` VALUES('1186', '1', '2019-06-20 22:05:15', '2019-06-20 15:05:15', '<h2>Annual Taxes</h2>		\n		<p>Every year on the 31st of March annual taxes need to be filed for every business. This is quite a complex process and we recommend hiring a professional firm to assist</p>		\n		<p><strong>Annual tax on profit</strong></p><p>At the end of the year, you will have to pay a tax for a total amount of 20% of your profit. You can then deduce the 1% you paid every month during the year.<br /><br /></p><p>Annual taxable profit in USD for a limited company:<br />&lt; 1,463 USD                     0%<br />1,463 – 3,658 USD          5%<br />3,658 – 24,878 USD       10%<br />24,878 – 36,585 USD     15%<br />&gt; 36,585 USD                   20%</p><p> </p><p><strong>Small Taxpayers</strong></p><p>The patent tax for sole proprietorships and partnerships is $100, which is approx. KHR400,000.</p><p><strong>Medium &amp; Large Taxpayers</strong></p><p>The patent tax is a fixed annual fee. It depends on which taxpayer category your company belongs to (small, medium or large). These are the official patent tax amounts:</p><p>Medium Taxpayer          KHR1,200,000/USD300</p><p>Large Taxpayer             KHR3,000,000 or KHR5,000,000*/ USD750 or USD1,250</p><p>*If the annual turnover of the Large Taxpayer exceeds KHR10,000 million (USD2.5 million) then the Patent Tax payable will be USD1,250.</p><p>If the annual turnover of the Large Taxpayer is less than KHR10,000 million (USD2.5 million) the Patent Tax payable will be USD750.</p>', 'Annual Taxes', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'annual-taxes', '', '', '2019-06-24 16:39:51', '2019-06-24 09:39:51', '', '0', 'http://maskred.com/BIGkeenProject/BK_ngeayngeay/?page_id=1186', '0', 'page', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `nge_posts` VALUES('1187', '1', '2019-06-20 22:05:55', '2019-06-20 15:05:55', '<h2>Ministry of Labour Registration</h2>		\n		<p>All business registered with the MoC and General Department of Tax need to be registered with the Ministry of Labour.</p>		\n		<p>To register at the Ministry of Labour you will need</p><ul><li>Tax Patent</li><li>Certificate of Incorporation</li><li>Employee List (see template here)</li><li>Ministry of Labour forms filled out</li></ul><p>Take all the documents to the building called “General Labour” or អគ្គការងារ, on level 3. The general Labour building is at the back on the right.</p><p> </p>		\n			<iframe frameborder=\"0\" scrolling=\"no\" marginheight=\"0\" marginwidth=\"0\" src=\"https://maps.google.com/maps?q=ministry%20of%20labour&amp;t=m&amp;z=14&amp;output=embed&amp;iwloc=near\" aria-label=\"ministry of labour\"></iframe>', 'Patent Tax', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '1186-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-06-20 22:05:55', '2019-06-20 15:05:55', '', '1186', 'http://maskred.com/BIGkeenProject/BK_ngeayngeay/2019/06/20/1186-revision-v1/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `nge_posts` VALUES('1188', '1', '2019-06-20 22:09:53', '2019-06-20 15:09:53', '<h2>Patent Tax</h2>		\n		<p>All business are required to pay patent tax when they register and each year thereafter. The patent tax is a fixed annual fee. It depends on which taxpayer category your company belongs to (small, medium or large).</p>		\n		<p><strong>Small Taxpayers</strong></p><p>The patent tax for sole proprietorships and partnerships is $100, which is approx. KHR400,000.</p><p>Deadline: End of March every year</p><p><strong>Medium &amp; Large Taxpayers</strong></p><p>The patent tax is a fixed annual fee. It depends on which taxpayer category your company belongs to (small, medium or large). These are the official patent tax amounts:</p><p>Medium Taxpayer          KHR1,200,000/USD300</p><p>Large Taxpayer             KHR3,000,000 or KHR5,000,000*/ USD750 or USD1,250</p><p>*If the annual turnover of the Large Taxpayer exceeds KHR10,000 million (USD2.5 million) then the Patent Tax payable will be USD1,250.</p><p>If the annual turnover of the Large Taxpayer is less than KHR10,000 million (USD2.5 million) the Patent Tax payable will be USD750.</p>', 'Patent Tax', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '1186-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-06-20 22:09:53', '2019-06-20 15:09:53', '', '1186', 'http://maskred.com/BIGkeenProject/BK_ngeayngeay/2019/06/20/1186-revision-v1/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `nge_posts` VALUES('1189', '1', '2019-06-20 22:11:48', '2019-06-20 15:11:48', '<h2>Monthly Tax &amp; NSSF Rates</h2>		\n		<p>Monthly Taxes are due at the 20th of each month, NSSF is due on the 15th of each month</p>		\n		<p>Below you will find summary tables of the monthly tax rates and NSSF rates. All monthly taxes are due on the 20th of each month, NSSF is due on the 15th of each month. </p><p>If you would like to estimate your monthly taxes, head to our tax calculator and let it estimate your monthly tax</p>		\n			<h2>VAT & Minimum Tax</h2>		\n		<table>\n						<colgroup>\n								<col span=\"1\">\n							</colgroup>\n		<thead>\n			<tr>\n			<th>\n							VAT & Minimum Tax						\n				</th>\n			<th>\n							Rate						\n				</th>\n						</tr>\n		</thead><tbody><tr>\n				<td data-title=\"VAT &amp; Minimum Tax\">\n					Value Added Tax				\n		</td>		<td data-title=\"Rate\" colspan=\"2\">\n					10%				\n		</td></tr><tr>\n				<td data-title=\"VAT &amp; Minimum Tax\">\n					Minimum Tax (Pre-Profit)				\n		</td>		<td data-title=\"Rate\">\n					1%				\n		</td></tr>\n			</tbody>\n		</table>\n			<h2>Tax on Salary</h2>		\n		<table>\n						<colgroup>\n								<col span=\"1\">\n							</colgroup>\n		<thead>\n			<tr>\n			<th>\n							Tax on Salary						\n				</th>\n			<th>\n							Rate						\n				</th>\n						</tr>\n		</thead><tbody><tr>\n				<td data-title=\"Tax on Salary\">\n					0 - 1,200,000 KHR (0 - 300 USD) 				\n		</td>		<td data-title=\"Rate\" colspan=\"2\">\n					0%				\n		</td></tr><tr>\n				<td data-title=\"Tax on Salary\">\n					1,200,001 - 2,000,000 KHR (300 - 500)				\n		</td>		<td data-title=\"Rate\">\n					5%				\n		</td></tr><tr>\n				<td data-title=\"Tax on Salary\">\n					2,000,001 - 8,500,000 KHR (500 - 2,125 USD)				\n		</td>		<td data-title=\"Rate\">\n					10%				\n		</td></tr><tr>\n				<td data-title=\"Tax on Salary\">\n					8,500,001 - 12,500,000 KHR (2,125 - 3,125 USD)				\n		</td>		<td data-title=\"Rate\">\n					15%				\n		</td></tr><tr>\n				<td data-title=\"Tax on Salary\">\n					more than 12,500,001 KHR (more than 3,125 USD)				\n		</td>		<td data-title=\"Rate\">\n					20%				\n		</td></tr><tr>\n				<td data-title=\"Tax on Salary\">\n					Non - Resident (flat rate)				\n		</td>		<td data-title=\"Rate\">\n					20%				\n		</td></tr>\n			</tbody>\n		</table>\n			<h2>Withholding Tax</h2>		\n		<table>\n						<colgroup>\n								<col span=\"1\">\n							</colgroup>\n		<thead>\n			<tr>\n			<th>\n							Withholding Tax						\n				</th>\n			<th>\n							Rate						\n				</th>\n						</tr>\n		</thead><tbody><tr>\n				<td data-title=\"Withholding Tax\">\n					Rent				\n		</td>		<td data-title=\"Rate\" colspan=\"2\">\n					10%				\n		</td></tr><tr>\n				<td data-title=\"Withholding Tax\">\n					Services				\n		</td>		<td data-title=\"Rate\">\n					15%				\n		</td></tr><tr>\n				<td data-title=\"Withholding Tax\">\n					Interest Payments (excluding interest paid by a domestic bank)				\n		</td>		<td data-title=\"Rate\">\n					15%				\n		</td></tr><tr>\n				<td data-title=\"Withholding Tax\">\n					Royalties (Dividends)				\n		</td>		<td data-title=\"Rate\">\n					15%				\n		</td></tr><tr>\n				<td data-title=\"Withholding Tax\">\n					Interest paid on fixed term deposit (by domestic bank)				\n		</td>		<td data-title=\"Rate\">\n					6%				\n		</td></tr><tr>\n				<td data-title=\"Withholding Tax\">\n					Interest paid on non-fixed term deposit (by a domestic bank)				\n		</td>		<td data-title=\"Rate\">\n					4%				\n		</td></tr>\n			</tbody>\n		</table>\n			<h2>Other Taxes</h2>		\n		<table>\n						<colgroup>\n								<col span=\"1\">\n							</colgroup>\n		<thead>\n			<tr>\n			<th>\n							Other Taxes						\n				</th>\n			<th>\n							Rate						\n				</th>\n						</tr>\n		</thead><tbody><tr>\n				<td data-title=\"Other Taxes\">\n					Fringe Benefit Tax				\n		</td>		<td data-title=\"Rate\" colspan=\"2\">\n					20%				\n		</td></tr><tr>\n				<td data-title=\"Other Taxes\">\n					Public Lighting Tax				\n		</td>		<td data-title=\"Rate\">\n					3%				\n		</td></tr><tr>\n				<td data-title=\"Other Taxes\">\n					Accomodation Tax				\n		</td>		<td data-title=\"Rate\">\n					2%				\n		</td></tr><tr>\n				<td data-title=\"Other Taxes\">\n					Tax on Property Rental				\n		</td>		<td data-title=\"Rate\">\n					10%				\n		</td></tr>\n			</tbody>\n		</table>\n			<h2>NSSF Rates</h2>		\n		<table>\n						<colgroup>\n								<col span=\"1\">\n							</colgroup>\n		<thead>\n			<tr>\n			<th>\n							NSSF (due on the 15th)						\n				</th>\n			<th>\n							Rate						\n				</th>\n						</tr>\n		</thead><tbody><tr>\n				<td data-title=\"NSSF (due on the 15th)\">\n					Occupational Risk Scheme				\n		</td>		<td data-title=\"Rate\" colspan=\"2\">\n					0.8% of wage				\n		</td></tr><tr>\n				<td data-title=\"NSSF (due on the 15th)\">\n					Health Care Scheme				\n		</td>		<td data-title=\"Rate\">\n					2.6% of wage				\n		</td></tr>\n			</tbody>\n		</table>', 'Tax & NSSF Rates', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'tax-nssf-rates', '', '', '2019-07-23 16:33:04', '2019-07-23 09:33:04', '', '0', 'http://maskred.com/BIGkeenProject/BK_ngeayngeay/?page_id=1189', '0', 'page', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `nge_posts` VALUES('1190', '1', '2019-06-20 22:12:28', '2019-06-20 15:12:28', '<h2>Ministry of Labour Registration</h2>		\n		<p>All business registered with the MoC and General Department of Tax need to be registered with the Ministry of Labour.</p>		\n		<p>To register at the Ministry of Labour you will need</p><ul><li>Tax Patent</li><li>Certificate of Incorporation</li><li>Employee List (see template here)</li><li>Ministry of Labour forms filled out</li></ul><p>Take all the documents to the building called “General Labour” or អគ្គការងារ, on level 3. The general Labour building is at the back on the right.</p><p> </p>		\n			<iframe frameborder=\"0\" scrolling=\"no\" marginheight=\"0\" marginwidth=\"0\" src=\"https://maps.google.com/maps?q=ministry%20of%20labour&amp;t=m&amp;z=14&amp;output=embed&amp;iwloc=near\" aria-label=\"ministry of labour\"></iframe>', 'Tax & NSSF Rates', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '1189-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-06-20 22:12:28', '2019-06-20 15:12:28', '', '1189', 'http://maskred.com/BIGkeenProject/BK_ngeayngeay/2019/06/20/1189-revision-v1/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `nge_posts` VALUES('1191', '1', '2019-06-20 22:19:23', '2019-06-20 15:19:23', '<h2>Monthly Tax &amp; NSSF Rates</h2>		\n		<p>All Tax and NSSF rates listed below</p>		\n		<p><strong>1. Minimum Tax</strong></p><p>Profit tax prepayment:</p><p>Every month, you need to pay the rate of 1% on your turnover of the previous month inclusive of all taxes, except for VAT.</p><p><strong>2. Withholding Tax</strong></p><p>Rental : 10%</p><p>Labour : 15%</p><p><strong>3. Value Added Tax (VAT)</strong></p><p>The standard rate of VAT is 10%. It applies to all supplies, excluding exports and non-taxable supplies. Exported goods from Cambodia and services consumed outside Cambodia are not subject to VAT tax. The VAT is charged to the client and then paid to the government.</p><p><strong>4. Salary Tax and Tax on Fringe Benefit</strong></p><p>A company that has employees has to withhold tax before paying the employees and to pay it to the tax administration the month after the salary is paid. The rate depends on the employee salary, as listed below.</p><p>Monthly salary (Riels) Rate:</p><p>0 – 1,200,000                          0%</p><p>1,200,001 – 2,000,000          5%</p><p>2,000,001 – 8,500,000          10%</p><p>8,500,001 – 12,500,000        15%</p><p>12,500,001 – upwards          20%</p><p>You can download the Salary Tax 2018 App here, it can calculate your salary tax</p><p><strong>5. Public Lighting Tax</strong></p><p>This is a tax on all alcohol and cigarettes. The rate is 3% of all sales.</p>', 'Tax & NSSF Rates', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '1189-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-06-20 22:19:23', '2019-06-20 15:19:23', '', '1189', 'http://maskred.com/BIGkeenProject/BK_ngeayngeay/2019/06/20/1189-revision-v1/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `nge_posts` VALUES('1192', '1', '2019-06-20 22:21:02', '2019-06-20 15:21:02', '<h2>Monthly Tax &amp; NSSF Rates</h2>		\n		<p>Monthly Taxes are due at the 20th of each month, NSSF is due on the 15th of each month</p>		\n		<p><strong>1. Minimum Tax</strong></p><p>Profit tax prepayment:</p><p>Every month, you need to pay the rate of 1% on your turnover of the previous month inclusive of all taxes, except for VAT.</p><p><strong>2. Withholding Tax</strong></p><p>Rental : 10%</p><p>Labour : 15%</p><p><strong>3. Value Added Tax (VAT)</strong></p><p>The standard rate of VAT is 10%. It applies to all supplies, excluding exports and non-taxable supplies. Exported goods from Cambodia and services consumed outside Cambodia are not subject to VAT tax. The VAT is charged to the client and then paid to the government.</p><p><strong>4. Salary Tax and Tax on Fringe Benefit</strong></p><p>A company that has employees has to withhold tax before paying the employees and to pay it to the tax administration the month after the salary is paid. The rate depends on the employee salary, as listed below.</p><p>Monthly salary (Riels) Rate:</p><p>0 – 1,200,000                          0%</p><p>1,200,001 – 2,000,000          5%</p><p>2,000,001 – 8,500,000          10%</p><p>8,500,001 – 12,500,000        15%</p><p>12,500,001 – upwards          20%</p><p>You can download the Salary Tax 2018 App here, it can calculate your salary tax</p><p><strong>5. Public Lighting Tax</strong></p><p>This is a tax on all alcohol and cigarettes. The rate is 3% of all sales.</p><p><strong>NSSF Rates</strong></p><p>There are two contributions for the National Social Security Fund that are to be made each month by the employer.</p><p><strong>The Occupational Risk Scheme</strong></p><p>The rate for occupational risk is 0.8% of the workers gross wage.</p><p><strong>The Health Care Scheme</strong></p><p>The rate for the Health Care Scheme is 2.6% of the workers gross wage.</p><p>All workers are to be registered with the NSSF within 3 days of beginning employment.</p><p>NSSF payment deadline: 15<sup>th</sup> of each month</p>', 'Tax & NSSF Rates', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '1189-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-06-20 22:21:02', '2019-06-20 15:21:02', '', '1189', 'http://maskred.com/BIGkeenProject/BK_ngeayngeay/2019/06/20/1189-revision-v1/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `nge_posts` VALUES('1193', '1', '2019-06-20 22:23:02', '2019-06-20 15:23:02', '<h2>Required Accounting</h2>		\n		<p>Once you register your business one of the most important requirements is clear and proper accounting.</p>		\n		<p><strong>Small Taxpayers (Sole Proprietors &amp; Partnerships)</strong></p><p>The requirements for small taxpayers are significantly less than they are for medium and large taxpayers. Small Taxpayers are required to have three books:</p><p><a href=\"http://ngeayngeay.co/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/Expenses-Day-Book-updated.xlsx\"><strong><em>Expenses Day Book</em></strong></a></p><p>This is the gathering of all the operational expenses made by the company, so basically everything that it buys. It can refer to: goods or services, raw materials, employee wages, utility bills…. This record has to be completed daily.</p><p><a href=\"http://ngeayngeay.co/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/Sales-Day-Book.xlsx\"><strong><em>Sales Day Book</em></strong></a></p><p>The Sales day book, also a daily record, refers to all the goods and services sold by the company.</p><p><strong><em><a href=\"http://ngeayngeay.co/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/Ngeay-Ngeay-Inventory-template.xlsx\">Inventory Book</a></em></strong></p><p>The inventory book is the count of the inventory of the business.</p><p>Other suggested but not legally required books are:</p><p><strong><em>Accounts Receivable</em></strong></p><p>This is any money that is owed to you</p><p><strong><em>Accounts Payable</em></strong></p><p>This is any money that you owe</p><p><strong><em>Assets Book</em></strong></p><p>Any equipment, furniture or machinery you buy that is over $100</p><p><strong>Medium &amp; Large Taxpayers</strong></p><p>As the tax filing that is required for medium and large taxpayers is significantly more complex than it is for small taxpayers we strongly recommend that you use official accounting procedures such as CIFRS and use a system such as Quickbooks, Xero or Banhji.</p><p>If you are new to book keeping and accounting, we recommend that you hire a professional to help you with these. See here.</p>', 'Required accounting', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'required-accounting', '', '', '2019-07-25 09:42:07', '2019-07-25 02:42:07', '', '0', 'http://maskred.com/BIGkeenProject/BK_ngeayngeay/?page_id=1193', '0', 'page', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `nge_posts` VALUES('1194', '1', '2019-06-20 22:23:46', '2019-06-20 15:23:46', '<h2>Ministry of Labour Registration</h2>		\n		<p>All business registered with the MoC and General Department of Tax need to be registered with the Ministry of Labour.</p>		\n		<p>To register at the Ministry of Labour you will need</p><ul><li>Tax Patent</li><li>Certificate of Incorporation</li><li>Employee List (see template here)</li><li>Ministry of Labour forms filled out</li></ul><p>Take all the documents to the building called “General Labour” or អគ្គការងារ, on level 3. The general Labour building is at the back on the right.</p><p> </p>		\n			<iframe frameborder=\"0\" scrolling=\"no\" marginheight=\"0\" marginwidth=\"0\" src=\"https://maps.google.com/maps?q=ministry%20of%20labour&amp;t=m&amp;z=14&amp;output=embed&amp;iwloc=near\" aria-label=\"ministry of labour\"></iframe>', 'Required accounting', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '1193-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-06-20 22:23:46', '2019-06-20 15:23:46', '', '1193', 'http://maskred.com/BIGkeenProject/BK_ngeayngeay/2019/06/20/1193-revision-v1/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `nge_posts` VALUES('1195', '1', '2019-06-20 22:28:20', '2019-06-20 15:28:20', '<h2>Required Accounting</h2>		\n		<p>Once you register your business one of the most important requirements is clear and proper accounting.</p>		\n		<p><strong>Small Taxpayers (Sole Proprietors &amp; Partnerships)</strong></p><p>The requirements for small taxpayers are significantly less than they are for medium and large taxpayers. Small Taxpayers are required to have three books:</p><p><em>Expenses Day Book</em></p><p>This is the gathering of all the operational expenses made by the company, so basically everything that it buys. It can refer to: goods or services, raw materials, employee wages, utility bills…. This record has to be completed daily.</p><p><em>Sales Day Book</em></p><p>The Sales day book, also a daily record, refers to all the goods and services sold by the company.</p><p><em>Inventory Book</em></p><p>The inventory book is the count of the inventory of the business.</p><p>Other suggested but not legally required books are:</p><p><em>Accounts Receivable</em></p><p>This is any money that is owed to you</p><p><em>Accounts Payable</em></p><p>This is any money that you owe</p><p><em>Assets Book</em></p><p>Any equipment, furniture or machinery you buy that is over $100</p><p><strong>Medium &amp; Large Taxpayers</strong></p><p>As the tax filing that is required for medium and large taxpayers is significantly more complex than it is for small taxpayers we strongly recommend that you use official accounting procedures such as CIFRS and use a system such as quickbooks, xero or banhji.</p><p>If you are new to book keeping and accounting, we recommend that you hire a professional to help you with these. See here.</p>', 'Required accounting', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '1193-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-06-20 22:28:20', '2019-06-20 15:28:20', '', '1193', 'http://maskred.com/BIGkeenProject/BK_ngeayngeay/2019/06/20/1193-revision-v1/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `nge_posts` VALUES('1196', '1', '2019-06-20 22:31:13', '2019-06-20 15:31:13', '<h2>Salaries &amp; Compensation</h2>		\n		<p>Everything you need to know about salaries and compensation in Cambodia</p>		\n		<p><strong>Fortnightly Payments</strong></p><p>As of January 1<sup>st</sup>, 2019, all businesses are required to pay their employees two times per month. The first payment shall be 50% of the employees’ net wage and the second payment shall contain the remaining net wages plus any benefits owed.</p><p><strong>Minimum Wage</strong></p><p>There is no official minimum wage in Cambodia, however the general consensus is that the minimum wage should be set at the Garment Industry minimum wage which is $182/month for a 48-hour week.</p><p><strong>Overtime</strong></p><p>Overtime is classified as any hours above the normal working hours, which at a minimum must be no more than 9 hours/day, and no more than 48 hours per week. Any hours worked above these hours or the hours agreed upon employment are deemed to be overtime.</p><p>Overtime must be paid at 150% of wages or 200% of wages if worked between 10pm and 5am.</p><p>Additionally, workers may be entitled to days in lieu, if they are need to work on a typical rest day, the employees are entitled to take another day off.</p><p><strong>Public Holidays</strong></p><p>All employees are entitled to public holiday leave according the public holiday sub-decree issued by the government. In the case a public holiday is on a Sunday, employees are entitled to take the following Monday off work.</p><p>If businesses are required to open on public holidays, employees can work voluntarily but are entitled to pay of 200% of their normal wage.</p>', 'Salaries & Compensation', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'salaries-compensation', '', '', '2019-07-23 11:12:08', '2019-07-23 04:12:08', '', '0', 'http://maskred.com/BIGkeenProject/BK_ngeayngeay/?page_id=1196', '0', 'page', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `nge_posts` VALUES('1197', '1', '2019-06-20 22:31:53', '2019-06-20 15:31:53', '<h2>Ministry of Labour Registration</h2>		\n		<p>All business registered with the MoC and General Department of Tax need to be registered with the Ministry of Labour.</p>		\n		<p>To register at the Ministry of Labour you will need</p><ul><li>Tax Patent</li><li>Certificate of Incorporation</li><li>Employee List (see template here)</li><li>Ministry of Labour forms filled out</li></ul><p>Take all the documents to the building called “General Labour” or អគ្គការងារ, on level 3. The general Labour building is at the back on the right.</p><p> </p>		\n			<iframe frameborder=\"0\" scrolling=\"no\" marginheight=\"0\" marginwidth=\"0\" src=\"https://maps.google.com/maps?q=ministry%20of%20labour&amp;t=m&amp;z=14&amp;output=embed&amp;iwloc=near\" aria-label=\"ministry of labour\"></iframe>', 'Salaries & Compensation', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '1196-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-06-20 22:31:53', '2019-06-20 15:31:53', '', '1196', 'http://maskred.com/BIGkeenProject/BK_ngeayngeay/2019/06/20/1196-revision-v1/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `nge_posts` VALUES('1198', '1', '2019-06-20 22:31:59', '2019-06-20 15:31:59', '<h2>Seniority Payments</h2>		\n		<p>The seniority payment (Prakas 443) is quite complex and there are some issues that are not 100% clear at this date.</p>		\n		<p><strong>Seniority payments vs Severance Payments</strong></p><p>There are now two terms for severance payments in the updated Labour Law, seniority payments and severance payments. Severance payments refer to <a href=\"http://ngeayngeay.co/contracts/\">Fixed Duration contracts</a> (FDC). Seniority payments refer to <a href=\"http://ngeayngeay.co/contracts/\">Unfixed Duration contracts</a> (UDC).</p><p><strong>Severance Payments (Fixed Duration Contracts)</strong></p><p>For employees under fixed duration contracts, a severance pay of 5% of the total wages due throughout the contract must be paid at the completion or termination of the contract.</p><p><strong>Seniority Payments (Unfixed Duration Contracts)</strong></p><p>Employees on unfixed duration contracts are entitled to seniority payments equal to 15 days of wages and fringe benefits per year. This is to be made over two payments over the year:</p><p>1<sup>st</sup> payment (June): 7.5 days of wages and fringe benefits to be paid each year</p><p>2<sup>nd</sup> payment: (December): 7.5 days of wages and fringe benefits to be paid each year</p><p><strong>Back Pay of Seniority Payments</strong></p><p>Employees who have been employed prior to 2019 are entitled to back pay of seniority payments for the course of their employment, however this is capped at a maximum of 6 month of the average base wage in each year of employment.</p><p>For the non-TGF industry, the back pay has been delayed until December 2021.</p><p><strong>Textile, Garment and Footwear (TGF) Industry</strong></p><p>For the textile, garment and footwear (TGF) manufacturing industry, employees are entitled to 30 days of back pay each year (to a maximum of 6 months).</p><p>Back pay is to be paid in two installments over the course of the year; therefore an employee that commenced employment before 2019 is entitled to receive two payments in June; 1 back pay payment of 15 days and one seniority payment of 7.5 days of wages.</p><p>The back pay of seniority payments begins in 2019 with the first payment due in June 2019.</p><p><strong>Non-TGF Industry</strong></p><p>For companies not in the TGF industry the back pay of seniority payments are equal to 6 days of wages per year of employment (to a maximum of 6 months). The timing of these payments are 3 days in June and 3 days in December.</p><p>For the non-TGF industry, the back pay has been delayed until December 2021.</p>', 'Seniority Payments', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'seniority-payments', '', '', '2019-07-23 11:12:16', '2019-07-23 04:12:16', '', '0', 'http://maskred.com/BIGkeenProject/BK_ngeayngeay/?page_id=1198', '0', 'page', '', '0');
