INSERT INTO `nge_posts` VALUES('1292', '1', '2019-06-22 16:47:40', '2019-06-22 09:47:40', '<h2>How to find capital?</h2>\nAt Ngeay Ngeay, this is is one of the most commonly asked questions we receive, “How can I get funding?”, “Where can I get capital?”\n\n<strong>How can I get funding?</strong>\n\nWhen entrepreneurs or small business owners ask us this, the first thing we ask back, is “What do you need funding for?” Often the answer is for the operations of the business, which to us means that they do not need external funding, but better cashflow management. There are only a few genuine reasons to need external funding,\n<ul>\n 	<li>you need capital to grow and you have a plan on how you are going to do this (eg. New shop, building a factory, expanding operations)</li>\n 	<li>you need an expensive piece of equipment</li>\n 	<li>in rare cases for emergency cashflow (but you need to seek proper financial advice).</li>\n</ul>\nIf you are not in any of these positions, but you feel you need funding, we recommend you read our information on cashflow management here.\n\nIf you are looking to grow, or you need equipment then you have a few options on where you can get funding.\n\n<strong>1. Personal Funds &amp; Family &amp; Friends</strong>\n\nThis is often the best option, if it is available, the reason is it less risky, if the business fails, you will not owe the banks or money lenders money. You can receive investment from family and friends, which can often be done at lower interest rates and family and friends will require less paperwork. However, you need to be sure that your family or friends understand the risk they are taking on and that investing in a small business is risky. Additionally, be clear about the terms of the loan or investment and make sure it is written down.\n\n<strong>2. Microfinance Institutions (MFI)</strong>\n\nDepending on how much money you need and what you need it for, often the next easiest option for funding is from MFI’s, however, you will often need some collateral for these loans and they have large interest rates, and many times will have hidden fees. See our article here on what to look for before you receive a loan.\n\n<strong>3. Banks</strong>\n\nSimilar to MFI’s, banks are a good choice for loans, however in our experience, it is more difficult to receive a loan from a bank. You will need some collateral, normally in the form of land, to secure your loan. The interest rates for bank loans are generally better than MFI’s but as mentioned much harder to receive.\n\n<strong>4. Grants</strong>\n\nThere are many grants in Cambodia for small businesses, particularly if your business can show that it benefits society in some way. Grants are usually funded by large NGO’s, governments, or foundations, most grants will have an application form that you will need to explain about your business, and what you will do the money. See <a href=\"http://ngeayngeay.co/funding-opportunities/\">Funding Opportunities</a> for updates on grants that come out.', 'Finding Capital - G', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '1057-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-06-22 16:47:40', '2019-06-22 09:47:40', '', '1057', 'http://maskred.com/BIGkeenProject/BK_ngeayngeay/2019/06/22/1057-revision-v1/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
