INSERT INTO `nge_posts` VALUES('1337', '1', '2019-06-22 17:52:54', '2019-06-22 10:52:54', '<h2>Seniority Payments</h2>		\n		<p>The seniority payment (Prakas 443) is quite complex and there are some issues that are not 100% clear at this date.</p>		\n		<p><strong>Seniority payments vs Severance Payments</strong></p><p>There are now two terms for severance payments in the updated Labour Law, seniority payments and severance payments. Severance payments refer to <a href=\"http://ngeayngeay.co/contracts/\">Fixed Duration contracts</a> (FDC). Seniority payments refer to <a href=\"http://ngeayngeay.co/contracts/\">Unfixed Duration contracts</a> (UDC).</p><p><strong>Severance Payments (Fixed Duration Contracts)</strong></p><p>For employees under fixed duration contracts, a severance pay of 5% of the total wages due throughout the contract must be paid at the completion or termination of the contract.</p><p><strong>Seniority Payments (Unfixed Duration Contracts)</strong></p><p>Employees on unfixed duration contracts are entitled to seniority payments equal to 15 days of wages and fringe benefits per year. This is to be made over two payments over the year:</p><p>1<sup>st</sup> payment (June): 7.5 days of wages and fringe benefits to be paid each year</p><p>2<sup>nd</sup> payment: (December): 7.5 days of wages and fringe benefits to be paid each year</p><p><strong>Back Pay of Seniority Payments</strong></p><p>Employees who have been employed prior to 2019 are entitled to back pay of seniority payments for the course of their employment, however this is capped at a maximum of 6 month of the average base wage in each year of employment.</p><p>For the non-TGF industry, the back pay has been delayed until December 2021.</p><p><strong>Textile, Garment and Footwear (TGF) Industry</strong></p><p>For the textile, garment and footwear (TGF) manufacturing industry, employees are entitled to 30 days of back pay each year (to a maximum of 6 months).</p><p>Back pay is to be paid in two installments over the course of the year; therefore an employee that commenced employment before 2019 is entitled to receive two payments in June; 1 back pay payment of 15 days and one seniority payment of 7.5 days of wages.</p><p>The back pay of seniority payments begins in 2019 with the first payment due in June 2019.</p><p><strong>Non-TGF Industry</strong></p><p>For companies not in the TGF industry the back pay of seniority payments are equal to 6 days of wages per year of employment (to a maximum of 6 months). The timing of these payments are 3 days in June and 3 days in December.</p><p>For the non-TGF industry, the back pay has been delayed until December 2021.</p>', 'Seniority Payments', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '1198-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-06-22 17:52:54', '2019-06-22 10:52:54', '', '1198', 'http://maskred.com/BIGkeenProject/BK_ngeayngeay/2019/06/22/1198-revision-v1/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `nge_posts` VALUES('1338', '1', '2019-06-22 17:53:28', '2019-06-22 10:53:28', '<h2>Seniority Payments</h2>		\n		<p>The seniority payment (Prakas 443) is quite complex and there are some issues that are not 100% clear at this date.</p>		\n		<p><strong>Seniority payments vs Severance Payments</strong></p><p>There are now two terms for severance payments in the updated Labour Law, seniority payments and severance payments. Severance payments refer to <a href=\"http://ngeayngeay.co/contracts/\">Fixed Duration contracts</a> (FDC). Seniority payments refer to <a href=\"http://ngeayngeay.co/contracts/\">Unfixed Duration contracts</a> (UDC).</p><p><strong>Severance Payments (Fixed Duration Contracts)</strong></p><p>For employees under fixed duration contracts, a severance pay of 5% of the total wages due throughout the contract must be paid at the completion or termination of the contract.</p><p><strong>Seniority Payments (Unfixed Duration Contracts)</strong></p><p>Employees on unfixed duration contracts are entitled to seniority payments equal to 15 days of wages and fringe benefits per year. This is to be made over two payments over the year:</p><p>1<sup>st</sup> payment (June): 7.5 days of wages and fringe benefits to be paid each year</p><p>2<sup>nd</sup> payment: (December): 7.5 days of wages and fringe benefits to be paid each year</p><p><strong>Back Pay of Seniority Payments</strong></p><p>Employees who have been employed prior to 2019 are entitled to back pay of seniority payments for the course of their employment, however this is capped at a maximum of 6 month of the average base wage in each year of employment.</p><p>For the non-TGF industry, the back pay has been delayed until December 2021.</p><p><strong>Textile, Garment and Footwear (TGF) Industry</strong></p><p>For the textile, garment and footwear (TGF) manufacturing industry, employees are entitled to 30 days of back pay each year (to a maximum of 6 months).</p><p>Back pay is to be paid in two installments over the course of the year; therefore an employee that commenced employment before 2019 is entitled to receive two payments in June; 1 back pay payment of 15 days and one seniority payment of 7.5 days of wages.</p><p>The back pay of seniority payments begins in 2019 with the first payment due in June 2019.</p><p><strong>Non-TGF Industry</strong></p><p>For companies not in the TGF industry the back pay of seniority payments are equal to 6 days of wages per year of employment (to a maximum of 6 months). The timing of these payments are 3 days in June and 3 days in December.</p><p>For the non-TGF industry, the back pay has been delayed until December 2021.</p>', 'Seniority Payments - G', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '1198-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-06-22 17:53:28', '2019-06-22 10:53:28', '', '1198', 'http://maskred.com/BIGkeenProject/BK_ngeayngeay/2019/06/22/1198-revision-v1/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
