INSERT INTO `nge_posts` VALUES('1390', '1', '2019-06-23 11:30:18', '2019-06-23 04:30:18', '<h2>How to find Start Up Capital</h2>		\n		<p>When we talk to budding entrepreneurs, one of the most common questions we get asked is how can I start a business if I don\'t have any money. Below you will find the most common ways to get startup capital for a new business</p>		\n		<p><strong>Using your own resources</strong></p><p>Many businesses do not need a lot of start up capital, and often your dream business can be scaled down so that you can begin with little money and build your way up. This is also a very good way of testing your target market, and your value proposition. Think about how you can save your money to start a very small business, and use the profits of that to save more to build a bigger business. Often many entrepreneurs in the beginning will have multipe jobs, they will have their normal job as well as run their business until they have enough capital to do their business 100%.</p><p><strong>Family and Friends</strong></p><p>Asking family and friend for money is one of the most common ways entrepreneurs can get started. Again, this will often mean that you have to start a smaller scale business until you can generate enough funds to start a bigger business, but this is a great way to start. </p><p><strong>Grants</strong></p><p>There are many grants that will help fund small businesses, if you have a unique idea then you can look at the many grants that come up in Cambodia to see if your idea fits with those.</p><p><strong>Micro-loans</strong></p><p>Micro-loans are some of the easiest loans to receive in Cambodia and this can be a great way to get started. You need to be very aware of the costs involved and watch out for any hidden costs. See our loan calculator to help you see how much you will pay in interest.</p><p><strong>Investment and Loans</strong></p><p>It is often very difficult to get investment and larger loans for a non-existing business, however it does happen occasionally. If you would like to talk further about investment please contact us at ngeayngeay.co and we can help direct you to investors.</p><p>See our <a href=\"http://ngeayngeay.co/funding-opportunities/\">Funding Opportunities</a> page for upcoming opportunities for your business</p><p> </p>', 'How to find startup capital - G', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '1295-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-06-23 11:30:18', '2019-06-23 04:30:18', '', '1295', 'http://maskred.com/BIGkeenProject/BK_ngeayngeay/2019/06/23/1295-revision-v1/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `nge_posts` VALUES('1391', '1', '2019-06-23 11:30:34', '2019-06-23 04:30:34', '<h2>Leave</h2>		\n		<p>There are various types of leave that employees are obligated to receive in Cambodia</p>		\n		<p><strong>Annual Leave</strong></p><p>Annual leave is provided to all employees once they have completed 1 year of service. Annual leave is on a pro-rata rate, of 18 days after 1 years service, based on a 48 hour work week. If the employee works less than 48 hours, for example, 40 hours, then the employee is provided 15 days of annual leave.</p><p>For every 3 years of service the employee is entitled to an extra day of annual leave per year.</p><p><strong>Weekly Rest</strong></p><p>All employees are entitled to 24 consecutive hours of rest per week</p><p><strong>Sick Leave</strong></p><p>The labour law requires a business to provide a sick leave to employees, if they have a letter from a certified doctor for up to 6 months, after 6 months the business can terminate the employee. The rates of pay for the employee during the sick period is as follows:</p><ul><li>During the 1st month of illness: 100% of wages,</li><li>During the 2nd and 3rd months of illness: 60% of wages,</li><li>During the 4th month and longer: no wages paid</li></ul><p><strong>Maternity Leave</strong></p><p>All women are entitled to maternity leave of 90 days, the employee is entitled to half the wages and benefits.</p><p><strong>Public Holidays</strong></p><p>All employees are entitled to public holiday leave according the public holiday sub-decree issued by the government. In the case a public holiday is on a Sunday, employees are entitled to take the following Monday off work.</p><p>If businesses are required to open on public holidays, employees can work voluntarily but are entitled to pay of 200% of their normal wage.</p>', 'Leave - G', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '1176-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-06-23 11:30:34', '2019-06-23 04:30:34', '', '1176', 'http://maskred.com/BIGkeenProject/BK_ngeayngeay/2019/06/23/1176-revision-v1/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `nge_posts` VALUES('1392', '1', '2019-06-23 11:32:39', '2019-06-23 04:32:39', '<h2>Ministry of Labour Registration</h2>		\n		<p>All business registered with the MoC and General Department of Tax need to be registered with the Ministry of Labour.</p>		\n		<p>To register at the Ministry of Labour you will need</p><ul><li>Tax Patent</li><li>Certificate of Incorporation</li><li>Employee List (see template here)</li><li>Ministry of Labour forms filled out</li></ul><p>Take all the documents to the building called “General Labour” or អគ្គការងារ, on level 3. The general Labour building is at the back on the right.</p><p> </p>		\n			<iframe frameborder=\"0\" scrolling=\"no\" marginheight=\"0\" marginwidth=\"0\" src=\"https://maps.google.com/maps?q=ministry%20of%20labour&amp;t=m&amp;z=14&amp;output=embed&amp;iwloc=near\" aria-label=\"ministry of labour\"></iframe>', 'Ministry of Labour Registration - G', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '1180-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-06-23 11:32:39', '2019-06-23 04:32:39', '', '1180', 'http://maskred.com/BIGkeenProject/BK_ngeayngeay/2019/06/23/1180-revision-v1/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `nge_posts` VALUES('1393', '1', '2019-06-23 11:33:02', '2019-06-23 04:33:02', '<h2>Monthly Taxes</h2>		\n		<p>Filing monthly taxes is a complex process for medium and large taxpayers. We highly recommend you hire a professional to assist you</p>		\n		<p>Each month you will have to pay your taxes, this includes your value added tax (VAT), tax on salary, minimum tax on profit, withholding tax and public lighting tax. Additionally you will need to pay your NSSF fees (see here).</p><p>Filing and payment of taxes in Cambodia for medium and large taxpayers is quite complex, we highly recommend that you hire a professional to assist you in this process. However, it is important you understand the basic process, as its your responsibility to ensure that all the taxes are paid correctly.</p><p>For small taxpayers (sole proprietors and partnerships), you only need to fill out one form. The instructions are found on the second page of the form.</p><p>For medium and large taxpayers, there are multiple forms and evidence that is required.</p><p>To file your taxes you need to download the appropriate forms found here. You will need to fill out all the forms and provide the necessary evidence, you need to hand these forms in, with payment to your local tax department for your Khan. Monthly taxes are due on the 20<sup>th</sup> of each month.</p><p><a href=\"http://ngeayngeay.co/tax-nssf-rates/\">For the latest tax rates, see here.</a></p>', 'Monthly Taxes-needs links to tax forms', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '1156-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-06-23 11:33:02', '2019-06-23 04:33:02', '', '1156', 'http://maskred.com/BIGkeenProject/BK_ngeayngeay/2019/06/23/1156-revision-v1/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `nge_posts` VALUES('1394', '1', '2019-06-23 11:33:24', '2019-06-23 04:33:24', '<h2>NSSF Registration</h2>		\n		<p>After registration with the Ministry of Labour, you will need to register with the NSSF</p>		\n		<p>For the NSSF registration you will need</p><ul><li>Tax patent</li><li>Certificate of Incorporation</li><li>Employee list</li><li>ID/Passport for the Chairperson/owner/representative of the business</li><li>NSSF Forms</li></ul><p>Go the General Labour or អគ្គការងារ building, level 3 and hand in the documents.</p>		\n			<iframe frameborder=\"0\" scrolling=\"no\" marginheight=\"0\" marginwidth=\"0\" src=\"https://maps.google.com/maps?q=ministry%20of%20labour&amp;t=m&amp;z=14&amp;output=embed&amp;iwloc=near\" aria-label=\"ministry of labour\"></iframe>', 'NSSF Registration - G', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '1183-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-06-23 11:33:24', '2019-06-23 04:33:24', '', '1183', 'http://maskred.com/BIGkeenProject/BK_ngeayngeay/2019/06/23/1183-revision-v1/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `nge_posts` VALUES('1395', '1', '2019-06-23 11:35:50', '2019-06-23 04:35:50', '<h2>Required Accounting</h2>		\n		<p>Once you register your business one of the most important requirements is clear and proper accounting.</p>		\n		<p><strong>Small Taxpayers (Sole Proprietors &amp; Partnerships)</strong></p><p>The requirements for small taxpayers are significantly less than they are for medium and large taxpayers. Small Taxpayers are required to have three books:</p><p><em>Expenses Day Book</em></p><p>This is the gathering of all the operational expenses made by the company, so basically everything that it buys. It can refer to: goods or services, raw materials, employee wages, utility bills…. This record has to be completed daily.</p><p><em>Sales Day Book</em></p><p>The Sales day book, also a daily record, refers to all the goods and services sold by the company.</p><p><em>Inventory Book</em></p><p>The inventory book is the count of the inventory of the business.</p><p>Other suggested but not legally required books are:</p><p><em>Accounts Receivable</em></p><p>This is any money that is owed to you</p><p><em>Accounts Payable</em></p><p>This is any money that you owe</p><p><em>Assets Book</em></p><p>Any equipment, furniture or machinery you buy that is over $100</p><p><strong>Medium &amp; Large Taxpayers</strong></p><p>As the tax filing that is required for medium and large taxpayers is significantly more complex than it is for small taxpayers we strongly recommend that you use official accounting procedures such as CIFRS and use a system such as quickbooks, xero or banhji.</p><p>If you are new to book keeping and accounting, we recommend that you hire a professional to help you with these. See here.</p>', 'Required accounting - needs links to partners', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '1193-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-06-23 11:35:50', '2019-06-23 04:35:50', '', '1193', 'http://maskred.com/BIGkeenProject/BK_ngeayngeay/2019/06/23/1193-revision-v1/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `nge_posts` VALUES('1396', '1', '2019-06-23 11:36:11', '2019-06-23 04:36:11', '<h2>Salaries &amp; Compensation</h2>		\n		<p>Everything you need to know about salaries and compensation in Cambodia</p>		\n		<p><strong>Fortnightly Payments</strong></p><p>As of January 1<sup>st</sup>, 2019, all businesses are required to pay their employees two times per month. The first payment shall be 50% of the employees’ net wage and the second payment shall contain the remaining net wages plus any benefits owed.</p><p><strong>Minimum Wage</strong></p><p>There is no official minimum wage in Cambodia, however the general consensus is that the minimum wage should be set at the Garment Industry minimum wage which is $182/month for a 48-hour week.</p><p><strong>Overtime</strong></p><p>Overtime is classified as any hours above the normal working hours, which at a minimum must be no more than 9 hours/day, and no more than 48 hours per week. Any hours worked above these hours or the hours agreed upon employment are deemed to be overtime.</p><p>Overtime must be paid at 150% of wages or 200% of wages if worked between 10pm and 5am.</p><p>Additionally, workers may be entitled to days in lieu, if they are need to work on a typical rest day, the employees are entitled to take another day off.</p><p><strong>Public Holidays</strong></p><p>All employees are entitled to public holiday leave according the public holiday sub-decree issued by the government. In the case a public holiday is on a Sunday, employees are entitled to take the following Monday off work.</p><p>If businesses are required to open on public holidays, employees can work voluntarily but are entitled to pay of 200% of their normal wage.</p>', 'Salaries & Compensation - G', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '1196-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-06-23 11:36:11', '2019-06-23 04:36:11', '', '1196', 'http://maskred.com/BIGkeenProject/BK_ngeayngeay/2019/06/23/1196-revision-v1/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `nge_posts` VALUES('1397', '1', '2019-06-23 11:36:30', '2019-06-23 04:36:30', '<h2>Seniority Payments</h2>		\n		<p>The seniority payment (Prakas 443) is quite complex and there are some issues that are not 100% clear at this date.</p>		\n		<p><strong>Seniority payments vs Severance Payments</strong></p><p>There are now two terms for severance payments in the updated Labour Law, seniority payments and severance payments. Severance payments refer to <a href=\"http://ngeayngeay.co/contracts/\">Fixed Duration contracts</a> (FDC). Seniority payments refer to <a href=\"http://ngeayngeay.co/contracts/\">Unfixed Duration contracts</a> (UDC).</p><p><strong>Severance Payments (Fixed Duration Contracts)</strong></p><p>For employees under fixed duration contracts, a severance pay of 5% of the total wages due throughout the contract must be paid at the completion or termination of the contract.</p><p><strong>Seniority Payments (Unfixed Duration Contracts)</strong></p><p>Employees on unfixed duration contracts are entitled to seniority payments equal to 15 days of wages and fringe benefits per year. This is to be made over two payments over the year:</p><p>1<sup>st</sup> payment (June): 7.5 days of wages and fringe benefits to be paid each year</p><p>2<sup>nd</sup> payment: (December): 7.5 days of wages and fringe benefits to be paid each year</p><p><strong>Back Pay of Seniority Payments</strong></p><p>Employees who have been employed prior to 2019 are entitled to back pay of seniority payments for the course of their employment, however this is capped at a maximum of 6 month of the average base wage in each year of employment.</p><p>For the non-TGF industry, the back pay has been delayed until December 2021.</p><p><strong>Textile, Garment and Footwear (TGF) Industry</strong></p><p>For the textile, garment and footwear (TGF) manufacturing industry, employees are entitled to 30 days of back pay each year (to a maximum of 6 months).</p><p>Back pay is to be paid in two installments over the course of the year; therefore an employee that commenced employment before 2019 is entitled to receive two payments in June; 1 back pay payment of 15 days and one seniority payment of 7.5 days of wages.</p><p>The back pay of seniority payments begins in 2019 with the first payment due in June 2019.</p><p><strong>Non-TGF Industry</strong></p><p>For companies not in the TGF industry the back pay of seniority payments are equal to 6 days of wages per year of employment (to a maximum of 6 months). The timing of these payments are 3 days in June and 3 days in December.</p><p>For the non-TGF industry, the back pay has been delayed until December 2021.</p>', 'Seniority Payments - G', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '1198-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-06-23 11:36:30', '2019-06-23 04:36:30', '', '1198', 'http://maskred.com/BIGkeenProject/BK_ngeayngeay/2019/06/23/1198-revision-v1/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `nge_posts` VALUES('1398', '1', '2019-06-23 11:38:39', '2019-06-23 04:38:39', '<h2>Monthly Tax &amp; NSSF Rates</h2>		\n		<p>Monthly Taxes are due at the 20th of each month, NSSF is due on the 15th of each month</p>		\n		<p><strong>1. Minimum Tax</strong></p><p>Profit tax prepayment:</p><p>Every month, you need to pay the rate of 1% on your turnover of the previous month inclusive of all taxes, except for VAT.</p><p><strong>2. Withholding Tax</strong></p><p>Rental : 10%</p><p>Labour : 15%</p><p><strong>3. Value Added Tax (VAT)</strong></p><p>The standard rate of VAT is 10%. It applies to all supplies, excluding exports and non-taxable supplies. Exported goods from Cambodia and services consumed outside Cambodia are not subject to VAT tax. The VAT is charged to the client and then paid to the government.</p><p><strong>4. Salary Tax and Tax on Fringe Benefit</strong></p><p>A company that has employees has to withhold tax before paying the employees and to pay it to the tax administration the month after the salary is paid. The rate depends on the employee salary, as listed below.</p><p>Monthly salary (Riels) Rate:</p><p>0 – 1,200,000                          0%</p><p>1,200,001 – 2,000,000          5%</p><p>2,000,001 – 8,500,000          10%</p><p>8,500,001 – 12,500,000        15%</p><p>12,500,001 – upwards          20%</p><p>You can download the <a href=\"https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.gdt.project.salarytax2018&amp;hl=en\">Salary Tax 2018 App</a> here, it can calculate your salary tax</p><p><strong>5. Public Lighting Tax</strong></p><p>This is a tax on all alcohol and cigarettes. The rate is 3% of all sales.</p><p><strong>NSSF Rates</strong></p><p>There are two contributions for the National Social Security Fund that are to be made each month by the employer.</p><p><strong>The Occupational Risk Scheme</strong></p><p>The rate for occupational risk is 0.8% of the workers gross wage.</p><p><strong>The Health Care Scheme</strong></p><p>The rate for the Health Care Scheme is 2.6% of the workers gross wage.</p><p>All workers are to be registered with the NSSF within 3 days of beginning employment.</p><p>NSSF payment deadline: 15<sup>th</sup> of each month</p>', 'Tax & NSSF Rates - G', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '1189-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-06-23 11:38:39', '2019-06-23 04:38:39', '', '1189', 'http://maskred.com/BIGkeenProject/BK_ngeayngeay/2019/06/23/1189-revision-v1/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
INSERT INTO `nge_posts` VALUES('1400', '1', '2019-06-23 11:42:32', '2019-06-23 04:42:32', '<h2>Why Register?</h2>		\n		<p>The rate of unregistered businesses is very high in Cambodia. The Cambodian government has been addressing this issue in recent years and working to make the registration process easier and cheaper. But why should you register?</p>		\n		<p><strong>Six Reasons Why You Should Register? </strong></p><p><strong>Peace of Mind</strong></p><p>One of the most common reasons why businesses come to us to register, is for peace of mind. Having an unregistered business is a constant concern for business owners, as that face the risk of fees and penalties when operating an unregistered business. These fees and penalties vary from monetary fines to the closing down of your business.</p><p><strong>Access to Markets </strong></p><p>The second most common reason why businesses come to us, is because they have just been turned down by a large customer because they were not registered. Registering your business means you will be more likely to access large contracts and customers and grow your business.</p><p>Example: a large client of your business wants you to supply your product to them, but they need to have an invoice with VAT.  This is because otherwise registered businesses will have to pay withholding tax on their purchases with is 15% compared with VAT which is 10% and they can offset.</p><p><strong>Improved Access to Finance</strong></p><p>Unless you own land that you can use as collateral, accessing finance from a financial institution can be very difficult for small and medium business owners, this becomes much more difficult if you are not registered. Most banks and investment firms will not invest or loan money to a business that is not registered.</p><p><strong>Improved ability to sell</strong></p><p>If you are looking to sell your business, it becomes much easier if it is registered as it is clear what the buyer is buying, it is legally protected and there are verifiable financial records. If you are not registered, you may not be able to sell as easily or for as much as the business is worth.</p><p><strong>Protect your business</strong></p><p>Through registration, your name and business is protected, you will have legal ways of fighting any business that copies your product or branding.</p><p><strong>Protect your business</strong></p><p>Being an ethical business means protecting your employees through labour rights. By registering you are required to pay NSSF on the behalf of staff, provide fair contracts, and provide annual leave and sick leave. This means that your employees will have job security and feel protected, not only is this good for your employees but is also the basis of a great staff culture and staff retention.</p><p>There are many reasons why you should register your business, but these six reasons are the most common reasons we see at Ngeay Ngeay. If you need help registering, please contact us at <a href=\"mailto:admin@ngeayngeay.co\">admin@ngeayngeay.co</a></p>', 'Why register -G', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '932-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-06-23 11:42:32', '2019-06-23 04:42:32', '', '932', 'http://maskred.com/BIGkeenProject/BK_ngeayngeay/2019/06/23/932-revision-v1/', '0', 'revision', '', '0');
